A virtual Parliamentary meeting to discusss the national assembly's upcoming programme has been hacked. The meeting was taking place via video conferencing app, Zoom. Porn images and videos appeared on the screen. Courtesy #DStv403 CAPE TOWN - A virtual Parliamentary meeting to discuss the National Assembly's upcoming programme has been hacked. The meeting was taking place via video conferencing app Zoom. Pornographic images and videos appeared on the screen. READ: SA lockdown: Parliament to resume with immediate effect It is understood some racial slurs were also directed at National Assembly Speaker Thandi Modise, who was chairing the meeting. The "meeting was temporarily disrupted by so-called 'bombers' or hackers," parliamentary spokesman Moloto Mothapo told AFP. "But (it) continued afterwards on a different platform." READ: Zoom vows to address privacy, safety issues after complaints Modise adjourned the virtual meeting, which resumed shortly afterwards on another platform. A meeting convened last month by Minister for Women, Youth and Persons with Disability Maite Nkoana-Mashabane was also bombarded with pornographic material. - Additional reporting AFP - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.